Univariate Exploration¶

Question: how the income range grows¶

In [21]:
sns.countplot(x=df["IncomeRange"], color="blue")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title("Income Range Growth", weight="bold", size=20);

Answer: The data consist of customers in decreasing order of the income hence one can say that people with higher income tends to borrow loan compare to people with less income. This cannot affirmative we will have to dig deep to show this¶

Question: Distribution of the debt to income ratio¶

In [22]:
sns.histplot(df["DebtToIncomeRatio"].dropna(), kde=True)
plt.xlim(0, 1)
plt.title("Distribution of Debt to Income Ratio", size=20, weight="bold");

Answer: The debt to income ratio is rightly skewed and majority of the record has a low debt to income ratio between the range of 0.1 and 0.3¶

Question: Population of the employment status and it effect on borrowing a loan¶

In [23]:
def countplot(data:pd.DataFrame, y_value: str, title: str, title_size: int, title_weight:str, order=None):
    sns.countplot(data=data, y=y_value, order=order)
    plt.title(title, size=title_size, weight=title_weight);
In [24]:
countplot(data=df, y_value="EmploymentStatus", title="Effect of Employment Status on the Loan", title_size=20, title_weight="bold")

Answer: The data gathered shows that employed individuals tends to feature the most. We also have non-employed individual featuring which could be due to stipends they recieve from family government etc.¶
